tic might be okay, but I think about using a public JDK bean class, like `java.awt.Point`, which has getters but no setters. Then there's `java.awt.Dimension`, which has setter methods. I could also think about using the `java.io.File`, which has a suitable constructor. Ultimately, I need a target bean with a File property that also has a setter.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_OPrTwMWBpeTZErThOA68Hhbl|fc_09d4f0bb442251090169f02014fd0881a38e46489da8c54df1\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/commons-collections/commons-collections/2.0/src/test/java/commons_collections/commons_collections/BeanMapTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"package commons_collections.commons_collections;\\n\\nimport org.apache.commons.collections.BeanMap;\\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\\n\\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\\n\\npublic class BeanMapTest {\\n    @Test\\n    public void readsAndWritesBeanProperties() {\\n        SampleBean bean = new SampleBean();\\n        bean.setName(\\\"before\\\");\\n        BeanMap beanMap = new BeanMap(bean);\\n\\n        assertThat(beanMap.get(\\\"name\\\")).isEqualTo(\\\"before\\\");\\n        assertThat(beanMap.put(\\\"name\\\", \\\"after\\\")).isEqualTo(\\\"before\\\");\\n\\n        assertThat(bean.getName()).isEqualTo(\\\"after\\\");\\n        assertThat(beanMap.get(\\\"name\\\")).isEqualTo(\\\"after\\\");\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    public void convertsValuesUsingSingleArgumentConstructors() {\\n        SampleBean bean = new SampleBean();\\n        BeanMap beanMap = new BeanMap(bean);\\n\\n        Object previousValue = beanMap.put(\\\"convertedValue\\\", \\\"converted\\\");\\n\\n        assertThat(previousValue).isNull();\\n        assertThat(bean.getConvertedValue().getValue()).isEqualTo(\\\"converted\\\");\\n        assertThat(beanMap.get(\\\"convertedValue\\\")).isEqualTo(new ConvertibleValue(\\\"converted\\\"));\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    public void clearReplaces